Love can never be comedic. Romance is incompatible with comedy. There might be joy, felicity, lightness, etc., but underneath true love is tragic and very serious. St. Ign. Brianchaninov said such "natural love" was sometimes expressed with a dagger. It is a very dangerous thing.

When Lancelot had an affair with King Arthur's wife, he became an instrument of Satan and brought ruin to the land. Swedenborg said Hell's chief pleasure was ruining marriages. When one loves conjugially, he makes enemy of the entire infernal realm, thenceforth unleashed upon him

The desire of the insomnious darkcel's heart is to be in a house or castle somewhere in the wilderness with many other people. A danger is revealed to be lurking in the night outside and he volunteers to keep vigil until sunrise, standing in front of the walls, on a balcony, etc.

One feels envy towards the guards in Hamlet's first acts. Midnight, sea roaring unseen in the distance, apparitions in the air, sword at one's hip. A friend of mine once kept watch over a villa with a knife in his hand all night while others slept, due to robbers stalking around.

I don't see anything comedic in it to be honest. The gnostic versions where Christ gets switched with an effigy or with someone else or survives somehow through trickery are comedic. The real one is deep tragedy, partly because it could have easily been prevented by Adam and Eve.

I understand why Fr. Rose despised Shakespeare's comedies and appreciated his tragedies. There is nothing comedic about the world. There is the possibility of eternal damnation and a lot of us are a random car crash away from it. And worst of all people drive like crazy nowadays.

Aristotle defined comedy as an imitation of men worse than the average (where tragedy was an imitation of men better than the average). However, the characters portrayed in comedies were not worse than average in every way, only insofar as they are Ridiculous, which is a species

"Tragedy" and "comedy" here in the Aristotelian sense of "imitating better than average men" versus "imitating worse than average men" or just producing tears versus producing laughter. If we're talking about happy and unhappy endings then no. A "tragedy" can have a happy ending.

Tears of sorrow are always admirable. Purity, ongoing sanctification, wounded, bleeding, objectivity. Laughter can be innocent, but there is always something animal in it, too crude. Tears of joy are the one ultimate emotion. Total purity, total felicity. They are almost inhuman.
There is nothing more beautiful than seeing someone cry in total happiness.

I dislike Joyce's "Araby" because Christmas markets, bazaars, and such always have something interesting as long as one has eyes to see. Reality is always, always better than the illusions and fantasies we make of it in our minds. God picked it after all. Leibnitz talks about it.

One texts from the 18th century (?) talked about how if one has an appetite for the spiritual, antiques, relics and sepulchers, he should starts with a simple walk through his town and he will be astonished what he will see and find. I would buy an Arabic vase with the shillings.

We should never forget our own survivability. You can probably be stabbed with a knife and run away holding your guts into the night. 72 hours of walking through winter woods chased by someone without sleep until you collapse alive at a small town gas station's doorstep. Survive.

No matter what happens you can probably survive by not sleeping for a few nights and running into the wild and staying awake not to succumb to hypothermia. Maybe lose a few toes, maybe suffer arthritis for life in your fingers, but we can make it alive out of most things.

Like those David Paulides cases where a child is found 8 days after going missing in a national park 400 miles away, half-dead half-alive, without shoes, after drinking mud to avoid dying of thirst. Infected, naked, diseased, scarred, but alive. Children are very good at survival
